[1]The Kawanishi E7K was a Japanese 1930s three-seat reconnaissance floatplane.
[3]Design and developmentIn 1932 the Imperial Japanese Navy requested the Kawanishi Aircraft Company to produce a replacement for the company's Kawanishi E5K.
[4]The resulting design, designated the Kawanishi E7K1, was an equal span biplane powered by a 462 kW (620 hp) Hiro Type 91 W-12 liquid-cooled inline engine.
Diagonal:2, Size:2
[7]The E7K1 was ordered into production as the Navy Type 94 Reconnaissance Seaplane ( ) and entered service in early 1935.
[8]It became a popular aircraft, but was hindered by the unreliability of the Hiro engine.
Diagonal:3, Size:2
[11]The earlier E7K1 was renamed to Navy Type 94 Reconnaissance Seaplane Model 1.
[13]The E7K2 continued in front-line service until 1943 and both versions were used in Kamikaze operations in the closing stages of the war.
